ations in CETA's Investment Chapter: Will Reform Enhance Legitimacy? -- tEnvironment, Energy, and Labour -- tCollaborative Governance for Addressing Climate Change: Evaluating CETA's Scope -- tThe Implications of CETA on Energy Systems in Canada: An Integrated Geographical View -- tTaming Regulatory Cooperation for the Protection of Labour Rights: The Case of CETA -- tConclusion: CETA Implementation Challenges and Trends -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Canada–European Union Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA) is hailed as the gold standard for trade agreements. It addresses tariffs on traded goods, favoured status for EU and Canadian exporters, trade in services, and technical barriers to trade, while also seeking coordination between government agencies to promote regulatory cooperation, harmonization, and mutual recognition of standards.As the world retreats towards populism and protectionism, CETA Implementation and Implications provides a vital examination of this contemporary economic collaboration between developed states, which serves as a model for other progressive regional trade agreements. This book offers the first in-depth, comprehensive assessment of CETA, covering many of its most important elements and exploring its obstacles, accomplishments, and early effects. Based on the European Commission-funded Erasmus+ Jean Monnet Project on CETA Implementation and Implications, which linked scholars and stakeholders across Europe and North America to analyze and evaluate the implementation and impacts of the agreement, this book covers regulation, procurement, the environment, the innovative investment disputes system, labour mobility and labour relations, bilateral governance instruments, and the implications for EU trade policy of CETA’s contested ratification.Uniquely interdisciplinary and featuring contributors from around the world, CETA Implementation and Implications provides a nuanced and balanced assessment of this landmark trade agreement and its effects on regional and global trade in turbulent times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aForeign trade regulationzCanada. 0aForeign trade regulationzEuropean Union countries. 0aForeign trade regulation. 0aInternational economic relations. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aCETA.  aCanada.  aEU treaties.  aEurope.  aICS.  aISDS.  aeconomics.  aenergy.  aenvironment.  agovernance.  ainvesterment disputes.  ainvestment.  alabour.  alaw.  apolitical science.  aprocurement.  apublic policy.  aregulation.  aregulatory cooperation.  atrade.1 aAcconci, Pia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhardwaj, Aakriti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamilleri, Mark A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinbow, Robert G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinbow, Robert G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGantz, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeblond, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMancini, Isabella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuffat, Agnès, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSantoire, Emmanuelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwartz, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwartz, Saul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStern, Felix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiß, Wol